README.md
     1â†’# python-dotenv
     2â†’
     3â†’[![Build Status][build_status_badge]][build_status_link]
     4â†’[![PyPI version][pypi_badge]][pypi_link]
     5â†’
     6â†’python-dotenv reads key-value pairs from a `.env` file and can set them as
     7â†’environment variables. It helps in the development of applications following the
     8â†’[12-factor](https://12factor.net/) principles.
     9â†’
    10â†’- [Getting Started](#getting-started)
    11â†’- [Other Use Cases](#other-use-cases)
    12â†’  - [Load configuration without altering the environment](#load-configuration-without-altering-the-environment)
    13â†’  - [Parse configuration as a stream](#parse-configuration-as-a-stream)
    14â†’  - [Load .env files in IPython](#load-env-files-in-ipython)
    15â†’- [Command-line Interface](#command-line-interface)
    16â†’- [File format](#file-format)
    17â†’  - [Multiline values](#multiline-values)
    18â†’  - [Variable expansion](#variable-expansion)
    19â†’- [Related Projects](#related-projects)
    20â†’- [Acknowledgements](#acknowledgements)
    21â†’
    22â†’## Getting Started
    23â†’
    24â†’```shell
    25â†’pip install python-dotenv
    26â†’```
    27â†’
    28â†’If your application takes its configuration from environment variables, like a
    29â†’12-factor application, launching it in development is not very practical because
    30â†’you have to set those environment variables yourself.
    31â†’
    32â†’To help you with that, you can add python-dotenv to your application to make it
    33â†’load the configuration from a `.env` file when it is present (e.g. in
    34â†’development) while remaining configurable via the environment:
    35â†’
    36â†’```python
    37â†’from dotenv import load_dotenv
    38â†’
    39â†’load_dotenv()  # reads variables from a .env file and sets them in os.environ
    40â†’
    41â†’# Code of your application, which uses environment variables (e.g. from `os.environ` or
    42â†’# `os.getenv`) as if they came from the actual environment.
    43â†’```
    44â†’
    45â†’By default, `load_dotenv()` will:
    46â†’
    47â†’- Look for a `.env` file in the same directory as the Python script (or higher up the directory tree).
    48â†’- Read each key-value pair and add it to `os.environ`.
    49â†’- **Not override** existing environment variables (`override=False`). Pass `override=True` to override existing variables.
    50â†’
    51â†’To configure the development environment, add a `.env` in the root directory of
    52â†’your project:
    53â†’
    54â†’```
    55â†’.
    56â†’â”śâ”€â”€ .env
    57â†’â””â”€â”€ foo.py
    58â†’```
    59â†’
    60â†’The syntax of `.env` files supported by python-dotenv is similar to that of
    61â†’Bash:
    62â†’
    63â†’```bash
    64â†’# Development settings
    65â†’DOMAIN=example.org
    66â†’ADMIN_EMAIL=admin@${DOMAIN}
    67â†’ROOT_URL=${DOMAIN}/app
    68â†’```
    69â†’
    70â†’If you use variables in values, ensure they are surrounded with `{` and `}`,
    71â†’like `${DOMAIN}`, as bare variables such as `$DOMAIN` are not expanded.
    72â†’
    73â†’You will probably want to add `.env` to your `.gitignore`, especially if it
    74â†’contains secrets like a password.
    75â†’
    76â†’See the section "[File format](#file-format)" below for more information about what you can write in a `.env` file.
    77â†’
    78â†’## Other Use Cases
    79â†’
    80â†’### Load configuration without altering the environment
    81â†’
    82â†’The function `dotenv_values` works more or less the same way as `load_dotenv`,
    83â†’except it doesn't touch the environment, it just returns a `dict` with the
    84â†’values parsed from the `.env` file.
    85â†’
    86â†’```python
    87â†’from dotenv import dotenv_values
    88â†’
    89â†’config = dotenv_values(".env")  # config = {"USER": "foo", "EMAIL": "foo@example.org"}
    90â†’```
    91â†’
    92â†’This notably enables advanced configuration management:
    93â†’
    94â†’```python
    95â†’import os
    96â†’from dotenv import dotenv_values
    97â†’
    98â†’config = {
    99â†’    **dotenv_values(".env.shared"),  # load shared development variables
   100â†’    **dotenv_values(".env.secret"),  # load sensitive variables
   101â†’    **os.environ,  # override loaded values with environment variables
   102â†’}
   103â†’```
   104â†’
   105â†’### Parse configuration as a stream
   106â†’
   107â†’`load_dotenv` and `dotenv_values` accept [streams][python_streams] via their
   108â†’`stream` argument. It is thus possible to load the variables from sources other
   109â†’than the filesystem (e.g. the network).
   110â†’
   111â†’```python
   112â†’from io import StringIO
   113â†’
   114â†’from dotenv import load_dotenv
   115â†’
   116â†’config = StringIO("USER=foo\nEMAIL=foo@example.org")
   117â†’load_dotenv(stream=config)
   118â†’```
   119â†’
   120â†’### Load .env files in IPython
   121â†’
   122â†’You can use dotenv in IPython. By default, it will use `find_dotenv` to search for a
   123â†’`.env` file:
   124â†’
   125â†’```python
   126â†’%load_ext dotenv
   127â†’%dotenv
   128â†’```
   129â†’
   130â†’You can also specify a path:
   131â†’
   132â†’```python
   133â†’%dotenv relative/or/absolute/path/to/.env
   134â†’```
   135â†’
   136â†’Optional flags:
   137â†’
   138â†’- `-o` to override existing variables.
   139â†’- `-v` for increased verbosity.
   140â†’
   141â†’### Disable load_dotenv
   142â†’
   143â†’Set `PYTHON_DOTENV_DISABLED=1` to disable `load_dotenv()` from loading .env
   144â†’files or streams. Useful when you can't modify third-party package calls or in
   145â†’production.
   146â†’
   147â†’## Command-line Interface
   148â†’
   149â†’A CLI interface `dotenv` is also included, which helps you manipulate the `.env`
   150â†’file without manually opening it.
   151â†’
   152â†’```shell
   153â†’$ pip install "python-dotenv[cli]"
   154â†’$ dotenv set USER foo
   155â†’$ dotenv set EMAIL foo@example.org
   156â†’$ dotenv list
   157â†’USER=foo
   158â†’EMAIL=foo@example.org
   159â†’$ dotenv list --format=json
   160â†’{
   161â†’  "USER": "foo",
   162â†’  "EMAIL": "foo@example.org"
   163â†’}
   164â†’$ dotenv run -- python foo.py
   165â†’```
   166â†’
   167â†’Run `dotenv --help` for more information about the options and subcommands.
   168â†’
   169â†’## File format
   170â†’
   171â†’The format is not formally specified and still improves over time. That being
   172â†’said, `.env` files should mostly look like Bash files. Reading from FIFOs (named
   173â†’pipes) on Unix systems is also supported.
   174â†’
   175â†’Keys can be unquoted or single-quoted. Values can be unquoted, single- or
   176â†’double-quoted. Spaces before and after keys, equal signs, and values are
   177â†’ignored. Values can be followed by a comment. Lines can start with the `export`
   178â†’directive, which does not affect their interpretation.
   179â†’
   180â†’Allowed escape sequences:
   181â†’
   182â†’- in single-quoted values: `\\`, `\'`
   183â†’- in double-quoted values: `\\`, `\'`, `\"`, `\a`, `\b`, `\f`, `\n`, `\r`, `\t`, `\v`
   184â†’
   185â†’### Multiline values
   186â†’
   187â†’It is possible for single- or double-quoted values to span multiple lines. The
   188â†’following examples are equivalent:
   189â†’
   190â†’```bash
   191â†’FOO="first line
   192â†’second line"
   193â†’```
   194â†’
   195â†’```bash
   196â†’FOO="first line\nsecond line"
   197â†’```
   198â†’
   199â†’### Variable without a value
   200â†’
   201â†’A variable can have no value:
   202â†’
   203â†’```bash
   204â†’FOO
   205â†’```
   206â†’
   207â†’It results in `dotenv_values` associating that variable name with the value
   208â†’`None` (e.g. `{"FOO": None}`. `load_dotenv`, on the other hand, simply ignores
   209â†’such variables.
   210â†’
   211â†’This shouldn't be confused with `FOO=`, in which case the variable is associated
   212â†’with the empty string.
   213â†’
   214â†’### Variable expansion
   215â†’
   216â†’python-dotenv can interpolate variables using POSIX variable expansion.
   217â†’
   218â†’With `load_dotenv(override=True)` or `dotenv_values()`, the value of a variable
   219â†’is the first of the values defined in the following list:
   220â†’
   221â†’- Value of that variable in the `.env` file.
   222â†’- Value of that variable in the environment.
   223â†’- Default value, if provided.
   224â†’- Empty string.
   225â†’
   226â†’With `load_dotenv(override=False)`, the value of a variable is the first of the
   227â†’values defined in the following list:
   228â†’
   229â†’- Value of that variable in the environment.
   230â†’- Value of that variable in the `.env` file.
   231â†’- Default value, if provided.
   232â†’- Empty string.
   233â†’
   234â†’## Related Projects
